{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527941"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:35:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:35:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14248"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14248"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.03,0.05,0.08,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53994"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6943"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14248"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39465"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2321"},{"type":"tags","id":"3996"},{"type":"tags","id":"4351"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43511"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53994"},"attributes":{"stem":"A 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for pre-pregnancy counselling. She has a medical history of epilepsy diagnosed six months ago, currently treated with lamotrigine. She initially presented with multiple episodes of loss of consciousness with stiffening of the body followed by uncontrollable jerking. Each episode usually lasted from seconds to two minutes, followed by confusion and exhaustion. Her medication is keeping her symptoms well controlled. She does not take any other regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate daily dose of folic acid supplementation for this patient in preparation for pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.4 mg","0.8 mg","1 mg","2.5 mg","5 mg"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor this patient with epilepsy who is planning pregnancy, the most appropriate daily dose of folic acid supplementation is \u003Cstrong\u003E5 mg\u003C/strong\u003E. This high-dose folic acid supplementation is recommended for women with epilepsy who are planning pregnancy or who are pregnant, regardless of the specific anti-epileptic medication they are taking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003E0.4 mg\u003C/strong\u003E dose is the standard recommended daily intake of folic acid for all women of childbearing age. However, this dose is insufficient for women with epilepsy due to their increased risk of neural tube defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E0.8 mg\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E1 mg\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E2.5 mg\u003C/strong\u003E doses, while higher than the standard recommendation, are still not sufficient for women with epilepsy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe 5 mg daily dose of folic acid is recommended for women with epilepsy because anti-epileptic drugs (AEDs) are associated with an increased risk of neural tube defects. This higher dose helps to mitigate this risk. It\u0027s important to note that while the patient is on lamotrigine, which is considered one of the safer AEDs during pregnancy, the high-dose folic acid recommendation still applies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to folic acid supplementation, it\u0027s important that this patient continues to be monitored closely during pregnancy. Lamotrigine levels can fluctuate during pregnancy due to changes in metabolism, and dose adjustments may be necessary. Regular follow-ups with both neurology and obstetrics will be crucial for optimal management of her epilepsy during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High-dose folic acid supplementation (5 mg daily) should be given to women with epilepsy planning pregnancy or who are pregnant."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Epilepsy in pregnancy (Green-top Guideline No. 68) [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2016 [cited 2024 Sep 28]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/media/rzldnacf/gtg68_epilepsy.pdf","Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Planning for pregnancy [Internet]. East Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2018 [cited 2024 Sep 28]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Planning-for-Pregnancy.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39465"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14248"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39465"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T16:08:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T10:44:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6943"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53994"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i